1
00:00:05,772 --> 00:00:07,641
Previously on "ER."

2
00:00:07,674 --> 00:00:09,242
Son of a bitch!

3
00:00:09,275 --> 00:00:11,612
I can be a competent surgeon.

4
00:00:11,645 --> 00:00:13,780
I can learn the techniques,
the mechanics..

5
00:00:16,282 --> 00:00:17,718
...but I'll never
be a great surgeon.

6
00:00:17,751 --> 00:00:19,485
Mark, I'm not gonna write
you that prescription

7
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:21,655
for the Percodan. I think
you've gotta get some help.

8
00:00:21,688 --> 00:00:23,123
I'm fine.

9
00:00:23,156 --> 00:00:25,491
Your baby was deprived
of oxygen in the womb.

10
00:00:25,526 --> 00:00:26,827
'So there's always
the possibility'

11
00:00:26,860 --> 00:00:28,294
'that there could
be brain damage.'

12
00:00:32,132 --> 00:00:33,133
Back off!

13
00:00:33,166 --> 00:00:35,702
Shut up! Shut up! Shut up!

14
00:00:38,438 --> 00:00:40,641
‐ 'Can we get this tonight?'
‐ 'We have to.'

15
00:00:40,674 --> 00:00:42,609
'Change out the batteries
in those lavaliers.'

16
00:00:42,643 --> 00:00:44,410
'He's getting
more nine‐volts.'

17
00:00:44,444 --> 00:00:47,280
‐ 'It's got the smell, huh?'
‐ 'Rob, white‐balance that.'

18
00:00:47,313 --> 00:00:50,250
'Tony already did it.
He laid down bars and tones.'

19
00:00:50,283 --> 00:00:52,619
'How come hospitals
have this smell?'

20
00:00:52,653 --> 00:00:54,621
'Pork buns?
Who went for food?'

21
00:00:54,655 --> 00:00:56,823
‐ 'I brought it myself.'
‐ 'Thanks a hell of a lot.'

22
00:00:56,857 --> 00:00:58,825
'Camera mount in the trauma
room's key‐stoning.'

23
00:00:58,859 --> 00:01:01,528
‐ 'Hasn't been leveled yet.'
‐ 'Alright, guys.'

24
00:01:01,562 --> 00:01:04,364
'Let's get ready to shoot.
Everybody on the same page?'

25
00:01:04,397 --> 00:01:06,132
‐ 'You worried about that?'
‐ 'No, it's working fine.'

26
00:01:06,166 --> 00:01:07,568
'Hey, hey!
Those tapes are numbered!'

27
00:01:07,601 --> 00:01:09,435
'Stuart and I will stick
with the doctor.'

28
00:01:09,469 --> 00:01:12,539
'Luis and Rob,
follow our lead.'

29
00:01:12,573 --> 00:01:14,708
'This is still breaking up.'

30
00:01:14,741 --> 00:01:16,643
'Remember our deadline. We don't
get a second chance here.'

31
00:01:16,677 --> 00:01:19,112
‐ 'I hate hospitals.'
‐ 'Is Dr. Greene here yet?'

32
00:01:19,145 --> 00:01:21,347
‐ 'I haven't seen him.'
‐ 'We'll catch up.'

33
00:01:21,381 --> 00:01:23,183
‐ 'Are you set in the lounge?'
‐ 'Just need tapes.'

34
00:01:23,216 --> 00:01:24,751
'Where do we put
the battery charger?'

35
00:01:24,785 --> 00:01:26,352
'It's plugged in
in the x‐ray room.'

36
00:01:26,386 --> 00:01:28,589
'Trim RF six,
it's too hot.'

37
00:01:35,295 --> 00:01:36,830
'What is that?'

38
00:01:36,863 --> 00:01:38,899
'Oh, you know,
it's back‐up footage.'

39
00:01:38,932 --> 00:01:41,467
'Workplace stuff.'

40
00:01:41,502 --> 00:01:42,736
Cubbies still losing?

41
00:01:42,769 --> 00:01:44,505
I don't know.
I haven't been watching.

42
00:01:44,538 --> 00:01:47,307
We put up stationary cameras,
one at your main desk

43
00:01:47,340 --> 00:01:48,675
one in that yellow
operating room.

44
00:01:48,709 --> 00:01:50,443
‐ Trauma one?
‐ Yeah, high‐traffic areas.

45
00:01:50,476 --> 00:01:52,913
Get some wide angles to cut with
what the hand‐held guys shoot

46
00:01:52,946 --> 00:01:54,180
for pace, variety, you know.

47
00:01:54,214 --> 00:01:55,516
Right.

48
00:01:55,549 --> 00:01:59,352
And we just leave them running.
Get what we get.

49
00:01:59,385 --> 00:02:00,821
It's on?

50
00:02:00,854 --> 00:02:03,824
By the end of the day
you'll forget we're here.

51
00:02:03,857 --> 00:02:05,726
See you.

52
00:02:05,759 --> 00:02:06,727
Excuse me.

53
00:02:13,767 --> 00:02:14,735
Oh!

54
00:02:19,673 --> 00:02:24,410
...in 1983 and again in 1986.

55
00:02:24,444 --> 00:02:28,381
Philadelphia in '83,
the New York Mets in '86.

56
00:02:28,414 --> 00:02:30,383
We'll see another
one right here.

57
00:02:34,220 --> 00:02:36,189
'I thought we were gonna start
with him coming on shift.'

58
00:02:36,222 --> 00:02:37,624
Too late.
He's already in trauma.

59
00:02:37,658 --> 00:02:38,725
Careful!

60
00:02:40,260 --> 00:02:41,261
He's the one
with the little glasses.

61
00:02:41,294 --> 00:02:42,596
'I remember.'

62
00:02:42,629 --> 00:02:44,264
Open fracture,
distal tibia.

63
00:02:44,297 --> 00:02:46,366
We gave four milligrams of
morphine in the field.

64
00:02:46,399 --> 00:02:47,801
How bad did
the goalpost look?

65
00:02:47,834 --> 00:02:48,969
Hey, I scored.

66
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:50,737
Nurse Marquez,
let's order pre‐op labs

67
00:02:50,771 --> 00:02:53,507
CBC, type and screen, and
left lower extremity films.

68
00:02:53,540 --> 00:02:54,541
Ancef?

69
00:02:54,575 --> 00:02:56,242
One gram IV piggyback

70
00:02:56,276 --> 00:02:57,544
and 100 of gentamicin.

71
00:02:57,578 --> 00:02:58,945
I really broke it, huh?

72
00:02:58,979 --> 00:03:00,480
You won't be playing
varsity this fall.

73
00:03:00,514 --> 00:03:02,448
Varsity?
I'm 24 years old.

74
00:03:02,482 --> 00:03:04,417
‐ Twenty‐four?
‐ Guess, I don't need you.

75
00:03:04,450 --> 00:03:07,320
Man, you are going
to get carded until you're 40.

76
00:03:07,353 --> 00:03:08,955
‐ Can you stay for a moment?
‐ You need me?

77
00:03:08,989 --> 00:03:11,457
Yeah, I want to get Dr. Greene
discussing the orders.

78
00:03:11,491 --> 00:03:14,695
‐ You need the back of my head?
‐ Yeah. That will be great.

79
00:03:14,728 --> 00:03:16,730
Uh, Dr. Greene,
how's that pulse?

80
00:03:16,763 --> 00:03:18,464
Distal pulses are
two plus and equal.

81
00:03:18,498 --> 00:03:20,233
No arterial injury.

82
00:03:20,266 --> 00:03:21,602
'Good evening.'

83
00:03:21,635 --> 00:03:23,403
Dr. Carter,
you're early.

84
00:03:23,436 --> 00:03:24,470
Open fracture?

85
00:03:24,505 --> 00:03:26,973
‐ Yup.
‐ Need me?

86
00:03:27,007 --> 00:03:30,777
Yes, uh, actually I'm sick of
assisting Dr. Welby here.

87
00:03:30,811 --> 00:03:32,546
Listen, why don't you
finish the history?

88
00:03:32,579 --> 00:03:34,948
Do you have pain anywhere
besides your leg, Mr. Chang?

89
00:03:34,981 --> 00:03:37,250
Justin.
I kind of jammed my stomach.

90
00:03:37,283 --> 00:03:38,619
Have you got
any allergies?

91
00:03:38,652 --> 00:03:40,020
Just hay fever.

92
00:03:40,053 --> 00:03:42,322
‐ Anything for me?
‐ Oh, this is today?

93
00:03:42,355 --> 00:03:43,590
'Please don't look
into the lens.'

94
00:03:43,624 --> 00:03:45,358
‐ Yeah, right.
‐ Possible surgical‐‐

95
00:03:45,391 --> 00:03:47,694
‐ You're still here?
‐ Yep. 36 hours.

96
00:03:47,728 --> 00:03:49,395
We're short a surgeon.

97
00:03:50,731 --> 00:03:52,699
Alright,
Belly's benign. Call ortho.

98
00:03:52,733 --> 00:03:55,401
How's it going?

99
00:03:55,435 --> 00:03:56,770
Is he pissed off
about losing you?

100
00:03:56,803 --> 00:03:58,038
We haven't talked.

101
00:03:58,071 --> 00:03:59,305
When was your
last meal?

102
00:03:59,339 --> 00:04:01,575
I ate lunch around one.

103
00:04:01,608 --> 00:04:04,277
‐ Cimetidine, 300 milligrams IV.
‐ You got it.

104
00:04:04,310 --> 00:04:06,379
That will cut down on the
acidity in your stomach.

105
00:04:06,412 --> 00:04:09,683
If you vomit in the OR,
you could aspirate your stomach

106
00:04:09,716 --> 00:04:11,618
contents into your lungs
and develop pneumonia.

107
00:04:11,652 --> 00:04:14,354
That's probably more
than Mr. Chang needed to hear.

108
00:04:14,387 --> 00:04:15,756
Whoa, whoa.
We've got a problem.

109
00:04:15,789 --> 00:04:17,457
‐ What.
‐ Sorry to interrupt.

110
00:04:17,490 --> 00:04:19,359
One of the docs says she wasn't
informed about our shoot.

111
00:04:19,392 --> 00:04:22,428
Alright. I'll be right there.
Stuart, are you okay?

112
00:04:22,462 --> 00:04:25,065
'Dr. Carter, uh, our mic will
pick you up at normal volume'

113
00:04:25,098 --> 00:04:26,767
'you can relax and
speak naturally.'

114
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:30,403
Okay, Carter wasn't acting.
He's really like that.

115
00:04:30,436 --> 00:04:33,640
They're focusing on Dr. Greene
but their goal is to get a sense

116
00:04:33,674 --> 00:04:36,009
of what all of us do
in the emergency department

117
00:04:36,042 --> 00:04:38,011
and portray it
in a positive light.

118
00:04:38,044 --> 00:04:40,013
It says nothing there
about a "Positive light."

119
00:04:40,046 --> 00:04:41,582
'It only talks
about their rights'

120
00:04:41,615 --> 00:04:43,016
'to use my name and
image in perpetuity.'

121
00:04:43,049 --> 00:04:44,585
Why not take this
in the lounge?

122
00:04:44,618 --> 00:04:46,553
You know, doctors Anspaugh
and Morgenstern

123
00:04:46,587 --> 00:04:48,722
think this documentary will
increase public awareness

124
00:04:48,755 --> 00:04:49,923
of the health care
issues we face.

125
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:51,792
Okay, I understand.
That's fine.

126
00:04:51,825 --> 00:04:53,059
I'm sorry,
what's your name?

127
00:04:53,093 --> 00:04:55,328
‐ 'Luis.'
‐ Luis. No offence, Luis.

128
00:04:55,361 --> 00:04:57,564
I'm not saying you're
ambush us or do any expose

129
00:04:57,598 --> 00:04:59,800
but there's nothing on
this form to stop them

130
00:04:59,833 --> 00:05:01,735
and if I don't sign this
you're wasting film right now.

131
00:05:01,768 --> 00:05:03,369
'It's tape.
It's cheap.'

132
00:05:03,403 --> 00:05:05,606
Hi. I'm Agi Orton. My husband
and I are the directors.

133
00:05:05,639 --> 00:05:06,807
Hi.
Anna Del Amico.

134
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:08,542
'Do you have
some questions?'

135
00:05:08,575 --> 00:05:10,611
If we could speak in the lounge,
it will all straighten out.

136
00:05:10,644 --> 00:05:11,912
Okay, sure.
I'll catch you later.

137
00:05:11,945 --> 00:05:13,980
You know, Dr. Del Amico
is new here..

138
00:05:14,014 --> 00:05:16,482
It's fine if she doesn't wanna
sign, we can shoot around her.

139
00:05:16,517 --> 00:05:17,784
Luis, if you're
finished setting up

140
00:05:17,818 --> 00:05:19,019
Stuart needs you.

141
00:05:19,052 --> 00:05:20,486
Hey, miss, is this
gonna be on TV?

142
00:05:20,521 --> 00:05:22,355
Uh, pre‐sold to PBS.

143
00:05:22,388 --> 00:05:24,057
PBS? Not Network?

144
00:05:24,090 --> 00:05:25,792
No. Luis.

145
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:29,796
That's not the point,
it's something Mark agreed

146
00:05:29,830 --> 00:05:31,497
and he's excited about it.

147
00:05:31,532 --> 00:05:34,501
‐ 'You think he's up to it?'
‐ Yeah, sure. Why not?

148
00:05:34,535 --> 00:05:36,069
Cameras all over the place.
It makes me uptight.

149
00:05:36,102 --> 00:05:39,039
I know. We'll all be hiding out
here by the end of the night.

150
00:05:39,072 --> 00:05:41,842
I don't know Mark the way you do
but he seems a little shaky.

151
00:05:41,875 --> 00:05:43,810
Oh, he's going
to be fine.

152
00:05:43,844 --> 00:05:46,412
Yeah, I'd be shaky, too if I had
the crap beaten out of me.

153
00:05:46,446 --> 00:05:49,149
'Mark wanted to do this.
I think that's a good sign.'

154
00:05:49,182 --> 00:05:51,384
‐ 'Maybe he's back on his game.'
‐ Maybe.

155
00:05:51,417 --> 00:05:52,953
In any case, they're here,
they're shooting.

156
00:05:52,986 --> 00:05:55,522
There's nothing we can do about
it except stick up for Mark

157
00:05:55,556 --> 00:05:57,991
which is what I'm doing.

158
00:05:58,024 --> 00:05:59,726
Buddy, you look like
a star out there.

159
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:01,795
Well, I'm enjoying
all the attention.

160
00:06:01,828 --> 00:06:04,030
Don't get too used to everybody
taking orders from you.

161
00:06:04,064 --> 00:06:05,666
Yeah, I was hoping
for a sequel.

162
00:06:05,699 --> 00:06:07,033
Yeah, well some of us
are working stiffs.

163
00:06:07,067 --> 00:06:08,535
I've got measles
in four.

164
00:06:08,569 --> 00:06:10,003
Later.

165
00:06:15,041 --> 00:06:16,777
Oh!

166
00:06:16,810 --> 00:06:17,778
Phew!

167
00:06:25,218 --> 00:06:27,187
Mr. Schoenberger
is in sinus rhythm.

168
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:31,958
BP's 110/70,
pulse is 72, reps are 16..

169
00:06:31,992 --> 00:06:34,094
...resps, uh, sorry.
Should I start over?

170
00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:35,529
'Sure.'

171
00:06:35,562 --> 00:06:37,864
Next time you can
just keep going.

172
00:06:37,898 --> 00:06:39,900
Oh, well, Mr. Schoenberger's
cardiogram is normal.

173
00:06:39,933 --> 00:06:41,001
His shortness of
breath was resolved

174
00:06:41,034 --> 00:06:42,836
with two liters
of oxygen.

175
00:06:42,869 --> 00:06:44,738
And he may have had slight
indigestion a couple hours ago.

176
00:06:44,771 --> 00:06:46,439
Today was
all‐you‐can‐eat burritos

177
00:06:46,472 --> 00:06:48,174
at my favorite
Mexican place.

178
00:06:48,208 --> 00:06:50,210
Do you have any family
history of heart disease?

179
00:06:50,243 --> 00:06:53,113
No. My relatives
generally prefer cancer.

180
00:06:53,146 --> 00:06:54,848
‐ Do you smoke?
‐ Not cigarettes.

181
00:06:54,881 --> 00:06:57,083
Mr. Schoenberger
recently took up cigars.

182
00:06:57,117 --> 00:06:58,151
I don't inhale.

183
00:06:58,184 --> 00:06:59,653
I started a cardiac work‐up

184
00:06:59,686 --> 00:07:01,154
ordered a CBC, chem seven.

185
00:07:01,187 --> 00:07:03,156
Cardiac enzymes,
serum myoglobin.

186
00:07:03,189 --> 00:07:04,758
Whoa, Jeanie,
that's a little gung‐ho

187
00:07:04,791 --> 00:07:06,527
for a guy who ate
too many burritos.

188
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:08,629
Well, he was concerned enough to
come in, and he has insurance.

189
00:07:08,662 --> 00:07:10,864
That's no reason
to order a million tests.

190
00:07:10,897 --> 00:07:12,733
You can lie back now.

191
00:07:12,766 --> 00:07:14,668
You know where I can get
a hold of any Havana's?

192
00:07:14,701 --> 00:07:18,805
Whoa! My tastes are
a little more pedestrian.

193
00:07:18,839 --> 00:07:20,641
I'm happy puffing
on one of these.

194
00:07:20,674 --> 00:07:22,509
No wonder you're
short of breath.

195
00:07:22,543 --> 00:07:24,778
Seriously? You think
it's the cigars?

196
00:07:24,811 --> 00:07:26,780
Those aren't fit
to be called cigars.

197
00:07:26,813 --> 00:07:28,782
You should lay off
the cheapos for a few days

198
00:07:28,815 --> 00:07:30,250
and I think
you're gonna feel fine.

199
00:07:30,283 --> 00:07:31,852
Give up the stogies?

200
00:07:31,885 --> 00:07:33,787
At least treat yourself
to something decent.

201
00:07:35,889 --> 00:07:37,924
Hey, you think
this'll be in the movie?

202
00:07:41,995 --> 00:07:43,664
I just dropped by
to thank you again, Mark

203
00:07:43,697 --> 00:07:45,832
and to see how
things are going.

204
00:07:48,001 --> 00:07:51,171
Y‐you don't
have to film this.

205
00:07:51,204 --> 00:07:52,506
Everything
under control?

206
00:07:52,539 --> 00:07:54,207
Yeah. Yeah, it is.

207
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:56,042
Seems like a pretty
busy night.

208
00:07:56,076 --> 00:07:59,546
Not that too busy...for
a weeknight.

209
00:07:59,580 --> 00:08:00,647
Right.

210
00:08:00,681 --> 00:08:02,082
It's pretty slow
for a weeknight.

211
00:08:02,115 --> 00:08:03,750
I'm sure it'll
pick up later.

212
00:08:03,784 --> 00:08:05,051
Yeah. Later.

213
00:08:05,085 --> 00:08:06,186
It should pick up.

214
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:07,954
You'll get good stuff.

215
00:08:07,988 --> 00:08:10,524
I just wanted to make sure
things were copasetic

216
00:08:10,557 --> 00:08:12,192
and thank you again
for taking this on.

217
00:08:12,225 --> 00:08:13,860
Sure.

218
00:08:15,929 --> 00:08:18,264
Stuart,
come grab this.

219
00:08:18,298 --> 00:08:19,299
Excuse me, who do
I give this to?

220
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:20,967
Oh, you
decided to sign?

221
00:08:21,001 --> 00:08:23,169
Yeah, just keep my face
off hard copy, okay?

222
00:08:23,203 --> 00:08:27,874
The nurses are cooking,
they're mic'd to channel three.

223
00:08:27,908 --> 00:08:29,676
The best one was the guy
with the transistor radio.

224
00:08:29,710 --> 00:08:31,077
‐ Remember?
‐ Right.

225
00:08:31,111 --> 00:08:32,613
He said he was
getting out of the shower

226
00:08:32,646 --> 00:08:34,648
he slipped and he
sat down on it.

227
00:08:34,681 --> 00:08:35,716
‐ Ouch.
‐ While it was still playing?

228
00:08:35,749 --> 00:08:38,284
Whoop, there it is.

229
00:08:38,318 --> 00:08:40,554
So I asked Mark,
Dr. Greene..

230
00:08:40,587 --> 00:08:42,255
...if he was going to
extract the foreign body

231
00:08:42,288 --> 00:08:45,291
and he said, "No, but I'll
tune it to the ball game!"

232
00:08:45,325 --> 00:08:48,294
Head lac for Carter,
has anybody seen him?

233
00:08:48,328 --> 00:08:51,297
'Is there's a camaraderie
between doctors and nurses?'

234
00:08:51,331 --> 00:08:53,199
‐ 'What about dating?'
‐ Who, Mark?

235
00:08:53,233 --> 00:08:54,334
'You tell me.'

236
00:08:54,367 --> 00:08:57,838
Oh...um..
Oh, I'm sorry..

237
00:08:57,871 --> 00:08:59,272
'Let me get that,
I got that.'

238
00:08:59,305 --> 00:09:02,142
Actually, we do socialize
but more as a group.

239
00:09:02,175 --> 00:09:05,011
And Dr. Greene comes...but he,
well, he used to come‐‐

240
00:09:05,045 --> 00:09:06,880
Well, he's been taking
it kind of slow.

241
00:09:06,913 --> 00:09:09,215
Yeah, since he got beat
down I mean, beat up.

242
00:09:09,249 --> 00:09:10,951
You know about
that, right?

243
00:09:10,984 --> 00:09:12,853
Mm.

244
00:09:12,886 --> 00:09:14,621
Well, you know what,
actually, it's a myth

245
00:09:14,655 --> 00:09:16,222
about doctors and
nurses dating so much.

246
00:09:16,256 --> 00:09:19,292
I mean, I know more nurses who
date cops, firemen, paramedics.

247
00:09:19,325 --> 00:09:21,194
Now, that cliche is true.

248
00:09:21,227 --> 00:09:22,863
Oh, especially cops.

249
00:09:22,896 --> 00:09:24,598
Especially young cops.

250
00:09:28,835 --> 00:09:30,003
'Getting back to Dr. Greene,
he does seem a little..'

251
00:09:30,036 --> 00:09:31,772
I need a nurse in three.

252
00:09:31,805 --> 00:09:34,641
'Oh, okay, everybody,
that was great.'

253
00:09:34,675 --> 00:09:36,910
'Lucy, you got
some explaining to do.'

254
00:09:36,943 --> 00:09:38,278
'What?'

255
00:09:38,311 --> 00:09:40,146
'What's all this
about cops and firemen?'

256
00:09:40,180 --> 00:09:41,214
Stay with them.
They're mic'd.

257
00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:42,315
'Jealous?'

258
00:09:42,348 --> 00:09:44,918
'Jealous.'

259
00:09:44,951 --> 00:09:46,019
I don't know what
you're doing for them

260
00:09:46,052 --> 00:09:47,654
you're not doing for me.

261
00:09:47,688 --> 00:09:48,955
I'll tell you later
if you bring the cuffs.

262
00:09:48,989 --> 00:09:50,390
I thought I was gonna
get some sleep tonight.

263
00:09:50,423 --> 00:09:52,192
Oh, don't count on that.

264
00:09:52,225 --> 00:09:53,627
Look at that.

265
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:55,862
He wishes he
could read lips.

266
00:09:55,896 --> 00:09:57,631
Hi, there, dumb ass.

267
00:09:58,699 --> 00:10:00,066
Doug, he's waving.

268
00:10:01,868 --> 00:10:03,303
You got a mic on?

269
00:10:03,336 --> 00:10:05,038
Oh, my God! Do you think
he could he hear me?

270
00:10:05,071 --> 00:10:07,073
Turn it off.

271
00:10:07,107 --> 00:10:10,243
But that's the thing
about the ER, you know

272
00:10:10,276 --> 00:10:11,878
You got to stay on your toes.

273
00:10:11,912 --> 00:10:14,214
‐ Hey, Lily's looking for you.
‐ I'm on my way.

274
00:10:14,247 --> 00:10:15,348
You're also more on
your own down here.

275
00:10:15,381 --> 00:10:16,883
When I was up in surgery

276
00:10:16,917 --> 00:10:19,352
there was always someone
looking over my shoulder

277
00:10:19,385 --> 00:10:20,821
critiquing every move.

278
00:10:20,854 --> 00:10:21,888
Here the residents
are responsible‐‐

279
00:10:21,922 --> 00:10:24,825
Carter! Help me.

280
00:10:24,858 --> 00:10:26,793
Get me a basin,
I can't get him rolled.

281
00:10:26,827 --> 00:10:28,428
I think I'm
gonna puke again!

282
00:10:28,461 --> 00:10:30,096
'I know..'

283
00:10:40,106 --> 00:10:42,275
‐ I feel much better.
‐ 'Oh, good. Good.'

284
00:10:42,308 --> 00:10:43,309
Oh, yeah.

285
00:10:43,343 --> 00:10:44,945
I'm going to change.

286
00:10:44,978 --> 00:10:46,780
Compazine for
our friend, please.

287
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:49,115
Twenty‐five milligrams PR.

288
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:50,350
Excuse me.

289
00:10:50,383 --> 00:10:52,052
'What's that mean, "PR"?'

290
00:10:52,085 --> 00:10:53,854
"Per rectum."

291
00:10:53,887 --> 00:10:55,421
'Do you have
to clean this up?'

292
00:10:55,455 --> 00:10:56,990
Oh, no.

293
00:10:58,224 --> 00:10:59,392
Housekeeping
to suture room.

294
00:11:00,927 --> 00:11:02,462
I don't know exactly
what you're looking for.

295
00:11:02,495 --> 00:11:04,230
We're just gonna keep it
really conversational.

296
00:11:04,264 --> 00:11:06,232
Everybody, come and go
as you normally would.

297
00:11:06,266 --> 00:11:08,001
Don't be afraid
to interrupt.

298
00:11:08,034 --> 00:11:11,371
Just talk right to me.
I'll be next to the camera.

299
00:11:11,404 --> 00:11:13,740
'First, explain how long
you've been here'

300
00:11:13,774 --> 00:11:14,808
'what an attending does.'

301
00:11:14,841 --> 00:11:16,209
My name's Mark Greene.

302
00:11:16,242 --> 00:11:17,944
And I've been working here
at County General

303
00:11:17,978 --> 00:11:20,781
since I finished med school
six years ago.

304
00:11:20,814 --> 00:11:23,116
I got the GI bleed in curtain
two admitted to medicine.

305
00:11:23,149 --> 00:11:25,085
Okay, great.
Thanks, Kerry.

306
00:11:25,118 --> 00:11:26,920
'Describe how an emergency
room serves the public.'

307
00:11:26,953 --> 00:11:29,022
Oh, well for a lot of people
we're the only access‐‐

308
00:11:29,055 --> 00:11:31,124
Mark, paramedics are pulling
in a 37‐year‐old male

309
00:11:31,157 --> 00:11:32,358
under respiratory distress.

310
00:11:32,392 --> 00:11:33,994
Neighbor called, he says
he's got cancer.

311
00:11:34,027 --> 00:11:36,229
Alright, prep trauma
one and find Carter.

312
00:11:36,262 --> 00:11:38,799
Oh, Mark, sorry, labs are
back on Schoenberger.

313
00:11:38,832 --> 00:11:40,200
‐ You'd better take a look.
‐ The cigar smoker?

314
00:11:40,233 --> 00:11:41,367
CKMBs are pretty high.

315
00:11:41,401 --> 00:11:42,468
I'll say.
Did he go home?

316
00:11:42,503 --> 00:11:44,304
He's getting
ready to go.

317
00:11:44,337 --> 00:11:45,972
‐ Dr. Del Amico?
‐ Yeah.

318
00:11:46,006 --> 00:11:47,908
Stick around, we have a
respiratory distress pulling up.

319
00:11:47,941 --> 00:11:49,510
I'm on it.

320
00:11:49,543 --> 00:11:51,745
Mr. Schoenberger,
we got your tests back

321
00:11:51,778 --> 00:11:55,248
with a result we didn't expect,
indicating a possible problem.

322
00:11:55,281 --> 00:11:56,850
What do you mean?

323
00:11:56,883 --> 00:11:58,484
You ought to stick around
for one more test.

324
00:11:58,519 --> 00:11:59,820
Troponin‐t.

325
00:11:59,853 --> 00:12:01,387
It's just for clarification.

326
00:12:01,421 --> 00:12:03,089
We can do it on the blood
we've already drawn.

327
00:12:03,123 --> 00:12:04,290
Better safe
than sorry.

328
00:12:04,324 --> 00:12:05,892
Exactly. And while
you're waiting

329
00:12:05,926 --> 00:12:07,293
we're gonna stick you
back on a monitor.

330
00:12:12,232 --> 00:12:14,134
An elevated CKMB

331
00:12:14,167 --> 00:12:16,036
indicates heart
muscle damage.

332
00:12:16,069 --> 00:12:17,871
‐ 'A heart attack?'
‐ That's right.

333
00:12:17,904 --> 00:12:20,874
‐ I'll get another EKG.
‐ 'Can it mean something else?'

334
00:12:20,907 --> 00:12:23,209
It's probably an MI. But the
other test will confirm it.

335
00:12:23,243 --> 00:12:24,878
'And then what?'

336
00:12:24,911 --> 00:12:27,380
Actually, regardless
of the other results

337
00:12:27,413 --> 00:12:30,416
an elevated CKMB,
means he's had an MI.

338
00:12:30,450 --> 00:12:33,153
So, I'm actually just
giving him a little time

339
00:12:33,186 --> 00:12:35,155
to adjust to that possibility.

340
00:12:35,188 --> 00:12:37,323
And, of course,
since I missed it

341
00:12:37,357 --> 00:12:39,993
I'm buying some time
to cover my ass.

342
00:12:43,029 --> 00:12:45,165
37‐year‐old man
in respiratory distress.

343
00:12:45,198 --> 00:12:46,466
Neighbor here says
he was diagnosed

344
00:12:46,499 --> 00:12:48,268
with esophageal cancer
six months ago.

345
00:12:48,301 --> 00:12:50,303
I was watching him
while Krista went to the store.

346
00:12:50,336 --> 00:12:51,972
He hasn't been
breathing that good‐‐

347
00:12:52,005 --> 00:12:53,940
‐ Out of the way!
‐ He started, like, choking..

348
00:12:53,974 --> 00:12:56,843
He's tachy at 120.
Pressure's 130/100.

349
00:12:56,877 --> 00:12:59,179
Resps are increased at 30.
He's got a lot of secretions.

350
00:12:59,212 --> 00:13:01,247
Alright, let's get him
on high‐flow O‐2

351
00:13:01,281 --> 00:13:02,482
and prep
an intubation tray.

352
00:13:02,516 --> 00:13:05,318
On my count,
one, two, three.

353
00:13:05,351 --> 00:13:08,188
Help him, he can't breathe.
Hang in there, Boz.

354
00:13:08,221 --> 00:13:10,156
Chuny, suction
these secretions.

355
00:13:10,190 --> 00:13:12,492
Hang two liters of saline,
this guy is bone dry.

356
00:13:12,526 --> 00:13:14,595
‐ Pulse ox is 89.
‐ Should I intubate?

357
00:13:14,628 --> 00:13:17,097
With the mass in his throat,
we'd have to crike him.

358
00:13:17,130 --> 00:13:18,498
But I don't want to use
extraordinary measures

359
00:13:18,532 --> 00:13:20,934
if he has a DNR.

360
00:13:20,967 --> 00:13:22,468
Do you know anything about
your best friend's wishes?

361
00:13:22,503 --> 00:13:24,871
He's the best bass
player I ever met.

362
00:13:24,905 --> 00:13:26,973
Yo, man, you can't light
that thing up in here.

363
00:13:27,007 --> 00:13:28,074
Keep suctioning.

364
00:13:28,108 --> 00:13:29,275
Anna, grab a blood gas.

365
00:13:29,309 --> 00:13:31,011
Pulse ox down to 87.

366
00:13:31,044 --> 00:13:35,148
Alright, prep a crike tray.
Give him 600 of clindamycin IV..

367
00:13:35,181 --> 00:13:37,150
‐ Carol, get the slate.
‐ Excuse me.

368
00:13:37,183 --> 00:13:38,885
‐ What's his name?
‐ Boz.

369
00:13:38,919 --> 00:13:40,954
Boz, can you hear me?

370
00:13:40,987 --> 00:13:42,455
I know you're having
trouble breathing.

371
00:13:42,488 --> 00:13:44,057
Do you want us
to help you out?

372
00:13:44,090 --> 00:13:46,359
‐ Antibiotics are up.
‐ I got to get in here.

373
00:13:46,392 --> 00:13:49,495
Sir, I'm gonna hold up this
slate, and you can write on it.

374
00:13:49,530 --> 00:13:53,033
Boz, do you want a
crichothyroidectomy?

375
00:13:53,066 --> 00:13:55,468
I can cut a hole in your
neck to help you breathe.

376
00:13:55,502 --> 00:13:57,504
Do you want that?

377
00:13:57,538 --> 00:14:00,273
If you can't write your answer
I'll have to put the tube in.

378
00:14:00,306 --> 00:14:02,976
Do you want
to be criked?

379
00:14:03,009 --> 00:14:04,310
Come on, don't let him die!
Give him the crike thing!

380
00:14:04,344 --> 00:14:08,148
Damn. I can't get this.

381
00:14:08,181 --> 00:14:10,350
‐ Okay, crike tray.
‐ Yeah, do it. Do it!

382
00:14:14,621 --> 00:14:18,358
No, no, no!
You do not want to know.

383
00:14:18,391 --> 00:14:20,093
'I wouldn't ask
if I didn't want to know.'

384
00:14:20,126 --> 00:14:22,563
I have done this
too long not to know.

385
00:14:22,596 --> 00:14:25,465
This job, people don't
want to hear about it.

386
00:14:25,498 --> 00:14:27,000
'Why? Because of what
you clean up?'

387
00:14:28,268 --> 00:14:29,903
This is nothing.

388
00:14:29,936 --> 00:14:33,540
Believe me, this here
is just a little...picnic.

389
00:14:33,574 --> 00:14:36,242
You ought to see
what some of them do.

390
00:14:36,276 --> 00:14:39,479
A body is only so big, but..

391
00:14:39,513 --> 00:14:42,315
...you can hardly believe
all that comes out of it.

392
00:14:44,084 --> 00:14:47,053
You get used to it though,
like every mama and daddy

393
00:14:47,087 --> 00:14:50,624
get used to changing
a baby's diaper.

394
00:14:50,657 --> 00:14:54,561
But the blood and the gore..

395
00:14:54,595 --> 00:14:57,564
You know what
the gore is, right?

396
00:14:57,598 --> 00:15:01,201
That's the part
you don't talk about

397
00:15:01,234 --> 00:15:05,271
when you go home and they
ask you how your day was.

398
00:15:05,305 --> 00:15:07,007
No, no.

399
00:15:08,074 --> 00:15:09,676
It doesn't bother me.

400
00:15:09,710 --> 00:15:13,346
You see, I'm a religious person

401
00:15:13,379 --> 00:15:15,582
and I believe human beings

402
00:15:15,616 --> 00:15:19,219
were created in God's image.

403
00:15:19,252 --> 00:15:23,957
So, whatever I'm cleaning up
must be just fine.

404
00:15:26,459 --> 00:15:28,128
Do you believe?

405
00:15:28,161 --> 00:15:29,362
'I don't know.'

406
00:15:29,395 --> 00:15:30,496
'You mean,
believe in God.'

407
00:15:30,531 --> 00:15:32,032
Uh‐huh.

408
00:15:32,065 --> 00:15:34,367
You couldn't do my job
if you didn't.

409
00:15:34,400 --> 00:15:36,102
You could maybe be a doctor

410
00:15:36,136 --> 00:15:39,640
or a nurse or make a movie.

411
00:15:39,673 --> 00:15:42,342
Not my job.

412
00:15:42,375 --> 00:15:44,410
Hey, I'll tell you
something else, too.

413
00:15:44,444 --> 00:15:46,212
Luis, we need you
in the trauma room.

414
00:15:46,246 --> 00:15:48,014
‐ A guy stopped breathing.
‐ I'm on my way.

415
00:15:50,416 --> 00:15:51,417
'I'll catch you later.'

416
00:15:51,451 --> 00:15:54,054
Sure, you will.

417
00:16:03,163 --> 00:16:05,999
Most of the ones I can remember
are from my first year.

418
00:16:06,032 --> 00:16:08,134
After a while,
you get protective

419
00:16:08,168 --> 00:16:10,036
and you don't let
them get to you.

420
00:16:10,070 --> 00:16:13,273
'What does it take these days to
break through your armor?'

421
00:16:13,306 --> 00:16:15,041
It doesn't happen.

422
00:16:15,075 --> 00:16:17,243
But there was this one
girl my first year.

423
00:16:17,277 --> 00:16:19,479
I guess I'd gotten used to
this being a County facility.

424
00:16:19,513 --> 00:16:21,047
I'd treated a lot
of homeless people

425
00:16:21,081 --> 00:16:23,049
a lot of people
from the projects.

426
00:16:23,083 --> 00:16:26,086
One day, this girl came in,
traffic accident

427
00:16:26,119 --> 00:16:29,690
in a coma, brain dead,
and I realized I knew her.

428
00:16:29,723 --> 00:16:33,126
She was the kid sister of a guy
I'd gone to med school with.

429
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:36,162
One night, she'd tried to show
me how to slam dance

430
00:16:36,196 --> 00:16:39,733
you know, just fooling around.
That's when I realized

431
00:16:39,766 --> 00:16:42,669
that trauma isn't something
that happens to other people.

432
00:16:42,703 --> 00:16:43,804
'It could happen
to you.'

433
00:16:43,837 --> 00:16:45,639
That's right.

434
00:16:45,672 --> 00:16:47,641
'Does it change things
when it is you?'

435
00:16:47,674 --> 00:16:49,375
What do you mean?

436
00:16:49,409 --> 00:16:51,277
'When you yourself
are traumatized..'

437
00:16:51,311 --> 00:16:53,179
'...as a doctor.'

438
00:16:53,213 --> 00:16:55,248
'I see you have a splint
on your wrist.'

439
00:16:55,281 --> 00:16:57,818
'I heard you had an incident
recently here at the hospital.'

440
00:16:57,851 --> 00:16:59,419
Is that what
you're doing here?

441
00:16:59,452 --> 00:17:01,121
‐ I don't wanna talk about that.
‐ 'I'm sorry.'

442
00:17:01,154 --> 00:17:02,723
But safety is something
everybody worries about.

443
00:17:02,756 --> 00:17:04,525
Is that why you picked me?
To get into all that?

444
00:17:04,558 --> 00:17:06,527
Dr. Green, we're not here to
make you uncomfortable.

445
00:17:06,560 --> 00:17:08,394
'You don't have to talk about
something if you don't want to.'

446
00:17:08,428 --> 00:17:10,463
‐ Good, because I'm not.
‐ 'But we are here.'

447
00:17:10,496 --> 00:17:12,265
And we are committed
to making this film.

448
00:17:12,298 --> 00:17:13,466
'And we want you
to have an opportunity'

449
00:17:13,499 --> 00:17:14,701
'to say what's
on your mind.'

450
00:17:14,735 --> 00:17:16,436
Yeah, well I have
nothing to say.

451
00:17:16,469 --> 00:17:18,171
I agreed to let
you follow me around

452
00:17:18,204 --> 00:17:20,574
you can do that, but no more
comments, no interview.

453
00:17:20,607 --> 00:17:22,242
Dr. Greene,
we are professionals.

454
00:17:22,275 --> 00:17:23,343
We're not here
to attack you.

455
00:17:23,376 --> 00:17:24,845
'Agi?'

456
00:17:24,878 --> 00:17:26,513
Damn.

457
00:17:28,248 --> 00:17:31,585
‐ 'Is that his daughter?'
‐ 'No, it's his wife.'

458
00:17:31,618 --> 00:17:34,420
'Esophageal cancer,
it's a horrible death.'

459
00:17:34,454 --> 00:17:35,656
Dr. Greene criked him.

460
00:17:35,689 --> 00:17:37,323
He's running
into surgical options

461
00:17:37,357 --> 00:17:38,725
and none of them are going
to buy him much time.

462
00:17:38,759 --> 00:17:40,160
Are you sure you want
to speak to the wife?

463
00:17:40,193 --> 00:17:41,795
She looks like
she's a teenager.

464
00:17:41,828 --> 00:17:45,231
It may be difficult to get her
to understand the situation.

465
00:17:45,265 --> 00:17:47,467
No, I'd like to try.

466
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:49,202
Normally, we wouldn't
have an intern take on

467
00:17:49,235 --> 00:17:51,872
something like this,
but Carter's been around.

468
00:17:51,905 --> 00:17:54,875
And technically, I'm not an
intern. I'm second year.

469
00:17:54,908 --> 00:17:57,778
‐ Uh, no, you're an intern.
‐ I am?

470
00:17:57,811 --> 00:18:00,547
You can't switch your specialty
here without starting over.

471
00:18:00,581 --> 00:18:02,382
‐ I've already done a year.
‐ In surgery.

472
00:18:02,415 --> 00:18:04,384
This is emergency medicine.
I thought you understood that.

473
00:18:04,417 --> 00:18:05,786
Uh..

474
00:18:05,819 --> 00:18:07,821
You know, let's, we'll
discuss this later

475
00:18:07,854 --> 00:18:10,090
when we're not in the
middle of all this.

476
00:18:11,892 --> 00:18:14,160
‐ 'Where do you start?'
‐ Huh?

477
00:18:14,194 --> 00:18:15,295
'When you have
to counsel family'

478
00:18:15,328 --> 00:18:16,630
'about something
like this.'

479
00:18:16,663 --> 00:18:18,498
Oh, yeah, well,
it's tricky, you know.

480
00:18:18,532 --> 00:18:19,666
People are upset,
and they're hearing

481
00:18:19,700 --> 00:18:21,535
a lot of complex information.

482
00:18:21,568 --> 00:18:23,469
An emergency resident..

483
00:18:23,504 --> 00:18:26,472
...or intern, has to establish
an instant rapport with the‐‐

484
00:18:26,507 --> 00:18:28,642
‐ Excuse me, doctor.
‐ No, not at all.

485
00:18:28,675 --> 00:18:30,711
I was just coming in
to see you.

486
00:18:30,744 --> 00:18:33,213
Um, your husband
is going to be admitted.

487
00:18:33,246 --> 00:18:34,447
Yeah, well, you'd
better call transport.

488
00:18:34,480 --> 00:18:36,149
They can take forever.

489
00:18:36,182 --> 00:18:38,384
Okay. Well, we should talk about
your husband's condition.

490
00:18:38,418 --> 00:18:39,886
Excuse me
for one second.

491
00:18:39,920 --> 00:18:43,590
